-- #326 regression: two impls of the SAME interface sharing ONE head tycon (`Box`),
-- with DIFFERING `requires`, both landing in the same `Foo|Box` receiver-head bucket.
-- `foo (Box 7)` dispatches to the MOST-SPECIFIC `impl Foo (Box Int)` (min⊑ over the
-- shared-head overlap), so obligation checking must discharge THAT impl's OWN
-- `requires Baz Int` — reporting `No impl of Baz for Int`.
--
-- The general `impl Foo (Box a) requires Bar a` is declared FIRST.  BEFORE #326 the
-- obligation checker was only PARTIAL min⊑: it ranked the concrete bucket before the
-- headless one, but WITHIN a shared head bucket it took DECLARATION-ORDER first-match
-- (`firstReqMatch`), so it selected `Box a`'s `requires Bar a` (→ `No impl of Bar for
-- Int`) — the WRONG impl's requirement, disagreeing with the dispatch ROUTER (PR #319),
-- which stamps `Box Int`.  #326 routes the checker's within-bucket selection through the
-- SAME shared min⊑ selector (`selectImplEntryByIface`) over the SAME all-impls registry
-- the router uses, so `check` now names the right impl's requirement.  The swapped
-- declaration order (overlap_same_head_req_wins_swapped.mdk) yields the IDENTICAL error,
-- which a declaration-order first-match could not.
interface Bar a where
  bar : a -> Int

interface Baz a where
  baz : a -> Int

interface Foo a where
  foo : a -> Int

data Box a = Box a

impl Foo (Box a) requires Bar a where
  foo _ = 0

impl Foo (Box Int) requires Baz Int where
  foo _ = 1

main = foo (Box 7)
